arks":1,"options":["Neurons in the paraventricular nucleus synthesise thyrotropin-releasing hormone","Thyrotropin-releasing hormone is produced in the median eminence","Thyroid-stimulating hormone is synthesised by somatotrophs","Thyroid hormones stimulate thyrotropin-releasing hormone release","Negative feedback occurs only at the pituitary gland"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid axis involves several key components working in concert:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurons in the paraventricular nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E of the hypothalamus produce thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH), which travels via the hypophyseal portal system to stimulate the anterior pituitary\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETRH is transported through portal vessels from the hypothalamus to the anterior pituitary, not produced in the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian eminence\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid-stimulating hormone is synthesised by somatotrophs\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - thyrotrophs, not somatotrophs, produce thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThyroid hormones suppress rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate thyrotropin-releasing hormone release\u003C/strong\u003E through negative feedback\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegative feedback occurs only at the pituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - thyroid hormones exert negative feedback at both hypothalamic and pituitary levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis complex system maintains precise control of circulating thyroid hormone levels through multiple feedback loops.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyrotropin-releasing hormone is produced by neurons in the paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus","Thyroid-stimulating hormone is produced by thyrotrophs in the anterior pituitary","Negative feedback occurs at both hy